{
  "text": "It may be useful to begin by recalling the classic analysis [CITATION_1] of the large N limit of a gauge theory. In 't Hooft's double line notation, each gluon propagator becomes a strip, and gauge theory Feynman diagrams take the aspect of \"fatgraphs\", or open string Riemann surfaces, classified by the genus g and the number h of holes (boundaries). The generating functional for connected vacuum diagrams has then the familiar expansion (assuming all fields are in the adjoint),",
